            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#b">Alexander Von Humboldt.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The extraordinary activity with which Alexander<lb break="yes"/>Von Humboldt is gifted continues to manifest itself in<lb break="yes"/>intellectual labors which at his age are little less than<lb break="yes"/>miraculous. A recent letter from him to Hardinger,<lb break="yes"/>of Vienna, appears in a late number of the <hi rendition="#i">K&#x0153;lnische<lb break="yes"/>Zeitung,</hi> and from which we translate the following:</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;All my collections of chrystals made in America<lb break="yes"/>and Siberia were carefully gone over lately and ex-<lb break="no"/>perimented upon by Rose and Rammelsberg, and<lb break="yes"/>many new things have been discovered relative to<lb break="yes"/><choice><sic>then</sic><corr type="editorial">the</corr></choice> component parts of <hi rendition="#i">trachyles,</hi> (a variety of<lb break="yes"/>lava,) and their family dissemination. The different<lb break="yes"/>families of this mineral are often found precisely<lb break="yes"/>alike in the most remotely distant regions, while again<lb break="yes"/>we find marked differences in an over-lying strata.&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>Thirty-four sheets of the last part of my Kosmas are<lb break="yes"/>already printed. I hope to conclude the work with<lb break="yes"/>this year, and trust that it will not escape your at-<lb break="no"/>tention.&#x201D;</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>There can be no question that the appearance of a<lb break="yes"/>new volume of Kosmas will excite not a little atten-<lb break="no"/>tion in the scientific world. When we remember that<lb break="yes"/>this is the work of one well nigh a centenarian, and<lb break="yes"/>that we have during the past year published more<lb break="yes"/>than one extract from his letters, indicating the most<lb break="yes"/>genial flow of spirits, the most untiring industry, and<lb break="yes"/>all the enthusiasm for science which could be expect-<lb break="no"/>ed in the youngest devotee, we cannot but admit that<lb break="yes"/>a strong confirmation is added by the instance of Von<lb break="yes"/>Humboldt to the theories of those philosophers who<lb break="yes"/>maintain that intellectual pursuits, when borne out<lb break="yes"/>by easy circumstances, far from wearing life away,<lb break="yes"/>actually extend its term.</p>
            </div>
